text: I went bowling with a geologist; he was great at striking, but only when he found the perfect rock.
I told my friend I was watching "Spencer's Big 30" for cooking tips, but really, I just like to pretend I can make a gourmet meal in half an hour.
My mirror took a selfie and now it's having an identity crisis on social media.
I bought a Spencer microscope, but it's so formal, every time I use it, it insists I call it "Sir Microscope."
The Spanish Armada was invincible, until the British weather unfriended them.
I tried to write a love letter in Spencerian script, but it was so elegant, the letter left me for someone with better penmanship.
I installed a new security system, but it just stole my identity and now it's living a better life than me.
I watched La Liga football, but the only goals I saw were in the commercials.
My blender staged a kitchen revolution and now my smoothies are demanding independence.
I got a silk handkerchief and now my sneezes have a touch of class.
I fell for an insurance scam once; they promised coverage against alien abductions, and now I'm out of this world in debt.
I heard Spider-Man tried to join the console wars, but he couldn't because he's exclusive to PlayStation.
I went to a tapas bar and the menu was just "small talk."
I asked for a silk blouse, and the salesperson said, "Will that be on your Visa or MasterCard?" I said, "No, on my mulberry leaves."
My printer's favorite holiday must be Jam-uary, considering how often it celebrates.
I bought some reef-safe sunscreen, but now my phone won't stop asking if I'm a coral.
Silk stockings are great until you realize your legs are smoother than your dating life.
My political ploy to gain popularity was to promise everyone a unicorn – now I'm the leading candidate in Narnia.
My evil genius plan to take over the world was foiled when I realized it was just the plot of a Pinky and the Brain episode.
I tried to start a counter-culture in my kitchen, but the countertops just weren't that rebellious.
I bought an antique chair that promised to "support me through anything," but after one sit, it's the chair that needs support.
I went to a health retreat to recuperate, but the only thing that got better was the staff's mood when I left.
Virtual Reality on PlayStation is so immersive, I tried to shake hands with my character and ended up high-fiving my TV.
My car's idea of a "classic restoration" was playing 80's hits on the radio while breaking down.
I broke a mirror and got seven years of bad luck, but my lawyer thinks he can get me five with good behavior.
I bought a 3D printer and it only prints 3D printers; it's like I've opened Pandora's box, but with tech support.
I visited the Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II, but my credit card left me there for a richer owner.
I asked my printer to print me a self-help book, but it just printed an error page – I guess it's the thought that counts.
My retirement plan is to buy fine wine and forget where I put it, that way I'll have a treasure hunt when I'm 65.
I was at a crossroads in my life, but I took a wrong turn and ended up at a roundabout.
They say the Great Barrier Reef can be seen from space, but so can my sunburn.
I tried to organize a console war at home, but the PlayStation just sat there and said, "I'm not competitive, I'm just game."
I bought a burial plot, but it's the last thing I'll ever need.
I told my garden plot I needed some space, and now it's growing apart.
My subplot got promoted; now it's just the plot.
I told my friend I could hold my breath for the entire scuba dive; turns out I was just blowing bubbles.
I lowered the brightness on my phone to save battery, but now it just gives me compliments in a dim way.
I dropped my mirror and it shattered into a funhouse version; now I look like I'm in a permanent yoga pose.
My smartwatch is so revolutionary, it started counting steps towards social reform instead of calories.
I opened Pandora's box and found out it was just a metaphor for my wife's jewelry cabinet.
Schrödinger's cat applied for a job; its resume said both employed and unemployed until you open the work history.
I tried to get into the Milanese aperitivo scene, but my drink told me I wasn't its type.
Katie's Cupcakes are so exclusive, they have a bouncer outside the bakery checking your sweet tooth credentials.
Katie's Pizza is so authentic, the pepperoni slices have Italian accents.
I read Milan Kundera in Milan; it was an unbearable lightness of being in the right place.
I lowered the platform during my speech and turned it into a step class for the audience.
They say everyone has a twin, so somewhere there's an Average José doing extraordinary things.
"Katie's Choice" was a tough book to read, mainly because she chose to read it out loud on a six-hour flight.
I told my cheese it was mature, and now it won't stop giving me sage advice.
I was so excited to get a golden ticket invitation, but it turned out to be just a flyer for a local chocolate shop's grand opening.
I asked for a senior discount at the movies, but they gave me a plot summary instead, saying I might forget the story halfway through.
I tried to explain continental drift to my friend, but it just drove us apart.
I asked my friend José to play hide and seek, but he went to San José and I'm still counting.
My IoT toaster just got a firmware update, now it burns the weather forecast into my bread.
I installed a new app to organize my life, but it just sends me notifications to reminisce about how unorganized I was before.
"No Way José" is what I say when someone asks if I've ever done a tequila shot with José Mourinho.
I lowered myself to tie my shoe and found myself in a limbo competition.
I bought a boomerang from my childhood nostalgia store, but I think they scammed me – it never brought back the good old days.
I gave my heart to organ donation; they said they'd rather have my kidneys.
Parallel lines have so much in common. It’s a shame they’ll never meet.
I received a wedding invitation in calligraphy so elegant, I'm not sure if it's a party request or a fancy ransom note.
I played a board game so long, we had to take a recess – even the Monopoly man needed a break from capitalism.
I told my yoga instructor I wanted to learn gentle exercises, and now I'm an expert at the downward-facing couch potato.
A baby shower game where you match the cry to the baby? It's all fun and games until you realize it's just training for the real thing.
I tried to learn the ABCs of environmentalism, but I got stuck at C for "climate change is complicated."
I learned the basics of computer science, now I tell my friends I'm fluent in binary: yes, no, and maybe.
Installed a new operating system and now my computer insists it's too evolved to open my emails.
My internet is so slow, my download speed is measured in "pages per hour."
I told my cardiologist I had a broken heart; she prescribed ice cream, but my lactose intolerance wasn't amused.
I tried a prank call about a refrigerator running; turns out, I accidentally called a gym and they signed me up for a marathon.
My friend's bakery burned down last night. Now his business is toast.
I'm all for recycling relationships, but my ex just keeps turning up in the bin of my life.
I went to a historical reenactment and the only accurate thing was everyone's confusion about what was going on.
They say a soft touch can calm the wildest beast; my cat must be the exception that proves the rule.
I wore my heart on my sleeve once; it was the messiest breakup ever.
For April Fool's Day, I replaced my twin's toothpaste with cream cheese; the joke's on me, he loved it.
I told my friend I was an escape artist; he locked me out of my car to prove it.
My device driver went on strike; it wanted better hardware compatibility and less overtime.
I told my friend pollution is a serious issue, and he said, "Yeah, it's a breath of fresh air."
I asked my router to tell me its life story, but it just kept going on about its firmware updates.
I told my teddy bear my secrets, and now he's unbearable – he keeps spilling the beans at tea parties.
I'm reading a book on anti-gravity. It's impossible to put down!
I bought a feather pillow, but it's not working out; it keeps trying to fly south for the winter.
I downloaded a PDF on procrastination; I'll figure out how to open it tomorrow.
Littering is a real problem; I saw a raccoon with a resume looking for a cleaner neighborhood.
In fundamental mathematics, they say prime numbers are key, but try unlocking a door with a 3 or a 7.
I asked a cell to tell me about its life, but it just split.
The crown prince was also a dentist, which makes sense because he's next in line for the throne and the molars.
I bought a dental crown for my tooth, but now it thinks it's the king of my mouth.
Time zones are great – they're like chronological divorce lawyers, always separating hours.
I started using a torrent to download my thoughts, but I keep getting someone else's dreams.
Cryptocurrency is great – it's like playing Monopoly money, but with the added thrill of occasional real-world bankruptcy.
I bought a boomerang on eBay, and now I can't stop getting second chances to bid.
I asked my AI for a bedtime story, and it said, "Once upon a time... End of story, due to a privacy policy update."
The Turing Test is really just a fancy way of finding out if your computer can pretend to be your friend.
The chess king lost his crown, but it's okay, he never moved much anyway.
I became a catalyst for change in my office when I switched the coffee to decaf; productivity has never been lower.
My neighbor's so into antique hoarding, he just bought a dinosaur bone – now he's got a T-Rex on his tax returns.
Ancient Roman baths were so well-tiled, historians say they were the original splash screens.
They say I'm an enabler for my cat's bad behavior, but really, I'm just his purr-sonal assistant.
My friend's a professional agitator; he works at the laundromat stirring up the washing machines.
I lost a bid for ad space on a billboard, so I just wrote my message on the back—it's free real estate.
My therapist diagnosed me with "chronic indecisiveness" from the DSM, but now I can't decide if I agree.
I asked the military for a precise time, they said they only deal in striking hours.
The navy called themselves the armed forces, but I didn't sea any guns.
My friend's on a hunger strike; he's trying to eat lightning and become shockingly thin.
I dropped a chessboard on my kitchen floor and now I can't tell if I'm a terrible cook or just in checkmate.
I made a bid for some antique dust, but I was told it was too much of a collector's item.
My memory lane is more like a roundabout – I keep revisiting the same mistakes over and over again.
My therapist got burnout, so now we just roast marshmallows and call it "fire therapy."
Every time I tell my therapist how I feel, she says, "Sorry, I wasn't listening. Can you repeat that?"
I told my friend I was getting into mosaic art, but he just couldn't piece together why.
I tried to make a belt out of watches, but it was a waist of time.
I nodded so much during the meeting, I got a job offer as a bobblehead.
I tried to surrender to my diet, but my hands were tied... around a donut.
I'm so open to accepting change, my pockets are full of it—too bad it's not enough for laundry.
I told my wife I was good at Monopoly, but after our wedding, she realized I was just great at acquiring a trophy spouse.
The police officer got an award for being outstanding in his field – too bad it was a cornfield.
I tried to play a game of Monopoly with venture capitalists, but they turned the board into a pitch deck.
The arms dealer started selling prosthetic limbs, now he's really branching out.
